{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_romeo_ver02/data/sn84026749/100492738/1907122901/0661.xml":{"full_text":"NEW YORK\u2014STOCKS, BONDS, AND MONEY\u2014WASHINGTON!\nhe\nNEW YORK STOCKS\nCLOSE SOME BETTER\nAFTER BAD WEEK\nSituation Shows Improve\nment, Although Far\nFrom Being Sat\nisfactory.\n\n\u2018New Year Will Feel Ef\nfects of 1907 Trou\nbles, and Reduced\nDividends.\nfold of another year the stock market\n\u2018assumed a better tone. This was par\ntially caused by the better bank state\n\u2018iment and the belief that much of the\n1$200,000,000 that will be paid out in the\nnext few days on account of interest\n\u2018and dividends will find its tay back\n\"into the market for reinvestment. More\nover, the stock market is now closely\nwatched by in-and-out traders, profes\ngeional and room traders, who are ready\nto follow any turn either way in the\nJmarket for scalping profit. If the prom\n\u2018fee is for higher prices they will buy,\nFbut no matter what the promise they\n{will take profits on the slightest indi\nNation of weakness.\nNEW YORK, Dec. 28.\u2014On the thresh\nThere are few among the old-time\n{traders on the market, and also among\nthe banking fraternity, who do not\nk with more or less dread on the\nfpossibilities of the year about to enter.\nThey fear the heritage of 1907.\n\u201cThe savings banks have proved their\nadvantage over the commercial insti\n{tutions in a way, because they, through\n\u2018their sixty days\u2019 notice policy, prac\n\"tically avoided being obliged to sacri\ndice their collateral, and with the ex\nfpiration of that time there has not been\njthe slightest desire on the part of de\n\n\nitors to draw down their desopits.\nWill Go Over to 1908.\nThe heritage that 1907 leaves to 18\nSs not a pleasant one. The great iron\nsteel industry is in a bad way with\nMaundreds of idle furnaces; railroads will\nfnot begin to do the business that they\ndid in 1907 because of the lesser volume\ntof freight; th. labor of the country is\nponly partially employed and In many\nces the \u201cfull dinner pail\u201d is endan\ngered. New York banks have millions\nof dollars of clearing house certificates\nto retire and this is also true of the\nin many of the leading cities.\ne premium on currency has about\n\u2018aisappeared. 80 in the gloomy situation,\nere is tnis much encouragement.\nOverexpansion has been pressed to\nfthe limit and for three months contrac\nrtion has been the order.\nMany banking institutions have been\n[wiped out and In the stock market\nralone, the estimates of securities\u2019 depre\nrciation has been placed at $3,000,000,000.\nPrices Have Discounted Conditions.\nTherein lies the safety and the hope\nwor the stock market for 1908. Not only\nas the water been squeezed out of\nties, but much genuine value lps\nbeen eliminated as well. Put it this\nway\u2014the market has discounted pres\nnt conditions. It is entitled to an im~\nement as the exports are rushed\nbroad and the gold this way\u2014it is but\nnatural reaction after months, over\near, of tobogganing. It is time that\nkonditions were responding to the prom\nMse of better times, but the response\n@must be slow and it must be gradual.\nThe foodstuff interests are satisfac\ntory. There seems to be plenty of buy\nHing power in the people and the holi\nMay trade attests that the prosperity\nof the last few years has not entirely\nFleft us, if it has hit the stock market\nja vengeful stroke.\nRailroad earnings are likely to com\nMrence to show a loss. Some of the\nock expansions of the past will make\nhe earnings of Hividends harder, but\nces are \u00a2n a reduced dividend basis.\nMany cash payments must be made\nHill stocks of \u2018recent Issuc, on New\nork Central and Missouri Pacific In\nhe near future, and these payments\nen run over into 1909.\nThe cutting of dividends, passing ot\nnterest payment periods and payment\n\u201cdividends and interest in scrip all\nto disturb confidence and keep\ne lid on the stock market\u2014to turn\nrally with a conservative reac\non\u2014anrd yet back of it all there is\ngth enough to keep the bears from\ntting too free with the list, strength\nenough or support on the part of the\n{finamcdal interests of the City of New\nYork, to prevent any runaway move\nnt, to make the declines slow and\nperadual.\nHope in Investment Buying.\nThe hope of the market is investment\nying\u2014actual purchasing of securities,\nng them out of the market and lock\nthem away in vaults, not to come\nt for months and years. There has\nfheen much of this buying of late and\ntthe stubbornness with which the list has\njyielded when yielding at all, has en\ncouraged them to make their purchases\nlittle more freely. A continued up\nturn would bring in a large number of\nving orders, but the leading financial\nterests in New York city do not want\nny great booms nor serious declines\u2014\nfact they would be best suited with\nduil, inactive market.\nThe year 198 is a Presidential year.\nie nothing of the cut and dried\nr in the campaign and surprises are\nle to be sprung, with the usual\nbt and uncertainty. This is another\nwhy the powers that be want\n8 to go slow, to fluctuate within a\nw range and to hold as steadily\npossible. The bears do not seem to\nas aggressive as they have been, but\nready to clean up accounts on short\nand every time they do they re\na sustaining influence from the\nthe\nDec. 28.\nWE 467%\n31%\n0...\" 19%\nA aN  T0%\nAtlantic Coast Line........ g0\nBalt. OR, es 17%\nCl Ora 30%\n8t. ban] HEPES 104%\nD. Hoi Goanzzeeestusmueess 146%\nIL iB al rthern............ 116%\nBake A PRS 90%\nNorthern Pac. 117%\nReading trrcrrrrentens PALIN 33%\nUnion  Pasifie..............0. 117%\ncom......... 26%\nSteel pf.... 87%,\n\nf\n\nend\n\nping\nhere\nason\nms\nder\nThe fact that the working balance of\nGovernment is getting low suggests\nearly calling of some millions of\nRhe\n#he\nmade bv the Secretary of the\nans\nr, as a re.ef measure\u2014the es\nNew York Stocks\n[Quotations furnished by Post Flags.\n[Rutibers New York Stock Exchange, .1331\nnw.\nOpen. High. Low..Noon.\n46% 46%\n0% Ss\n2 od\n70% 703g\n2 x\niy 2g\n70% 70%\n63 69\n81% S17%\n33% 38%\n30% 30%\no1ts 10843\n106% 1\n20 19% 19%\n2% 2 22%\nCol. Sou, 1st pid ode 49% 49% 9%\nCol. Sou. om 413, 40% 4\nConl. Gas XN. a 973, 95% 96%\nDel. Hudson...... 145 1464; 146 146%\nDeny. R. G......... 20% 21% 20% 21's\nDistillers Corp........ 20% 30% 29% 30\nBle vor vetsnsssanunaeas 16% 16% 16% 16%\nErie, 180 pid..counserss Hp BH Hk\nKON. IRIS, aves saan res 11234 112% 112 112\nGt. Nor. pri APPR IW 4 116% He 116 116%\nKansas C. pe...) D2 D2 HN, B2%\nLouis. gH WER 8 Me 92% 92\nMexican Cent.......... 14% 147%; 14% 17%\nMo., K. Tex. i WB 26 Hg 5%\nMissouri Pac... er 4TH, 8B 461, 451\nNat'l-Toaf:......o.. 4 391, 3995 30g 39g\nNOPE \"A. orn secs nnd 43 43\nN. XY. Alr Brake...... bl14 51 5 30\nN. Senta hast eee ie 91 04 ne\nN. Y.-C West... 33 33% 32%\nNorf. West.. eneeni/ Oh 643% 64 64%\nNor. Pas... aun wr spiia 118% 119% 117% 117%\nNorthwest ......ccccansd 13614\nPac. Mall.....\nPenn. R. R...\nAmal. Copper.......... 48\nAm. Car PFuicisaces 30%, 313;\nAm. Ice Sec..... paseyen RE\nAm. Loco....... Megs ense 0% 6\nAR. Belt... une ceas cons 70% 72\nAm, Smelt. Ple.osesssss 92 2\nAm. Bugar........ oenn 1000 10114\nADAGCORAR +oviesesss ies B 12 30%\nRIGIIBOR \u00abassess sigssense Tie 71%\nAt. Coast lL...... densa 69 65\nBalto. Ohlo.......... 821% 821%\nBk, Rpd. Trans....... 39% 40%\nChess. Ohlo.......... 30% 30%\nCh\" G. West. .....cons T%\nClee\u2019 My B Bt. Puvesea 106\n\u00a330). BPs ereevecsenes 19%\nBOR vee ernsaacn 21\n\nsn\n115% 119% 119%\nPeople's Gas.\nWig 9% ia 9%\nReading\nCareciccerss 181\u00a2 18%: 18% 18%\nMg 85% 93% 93%\nRep. B 3......0000ne\n18% 163% 16% 16%\nRep. 8S. 1., prd\n66 66 6 66\nROCK: Jei.vsssavssssssses\n15% 16% 15% 16%\nROCK 1. RRQ. conesevesys\nSouth. Pac............. Thy T485 TI TI/s\nScuth. Pac., pfd...... 100%; 1081; 109%; 109%\nTex. Pag...lcaneriorcss 1955 19% 196; 19%\nUnion Pacific.. 119 119% 117% 117%\nU8. C.L Pooccccsnres 20% 2005 2044\nBe RUBE. coe cess 21 21 Wy\nU.S Stoel... occur ese 263, 21 26%\n265\ntl. 8B. Bleal, Df..ccisers 88 87% 87%\nXabagh ....cs 00s euat 0 HN WH\nWabash, pf... co. sesees 18 18 18 18\nMISCELLANEOUS BON\n\nU. B. Bet] B'S. .pvess us 843, 5 84% 85\nBB easnsrctsenenss B89\ntimate of the amount generally agree\ning on a draft on depositories of some\n$25,000,000 for a starter\u2014taken out with\nas much reference to preventing dis\nturbances as possible.\nWhile conditions have been and are\nJust as stated, there is unquestionably\na better feeling among brokers and a\nmore hopeful tendency\nThe week has been also characterized\n\u2018more or less by dullness. For a time\nin the opening there was some evening\nup for the holiday, then on Thursday,\nwith New York Central plans uncertain\nand Missouri Pacific's dividend paid In\nstock, Distillers\u2019 dividend reduced, and\nsome fresh commercial disturbances, the\nmarket broke to the low point, losing\nthe earlier gains.\nSaturday's market in the opening; hour\nagain showed excellent strength. but\nmuch of the advances were lost in\nprofit-taking, which, as before Stateq,\nIs a positive feature of rises.\nAs compared with the closing prices\nof a week ago today, the changes are\nbY no means severe one way or the\nother. Some stocks are lower, but there\nar\u00e9 no radical changes in the list, as\nshown by the following tables.\nAs the market closed, the traders and\nbrokers, who for the first time in years,\nfailed to do stunts and spend much\nmoney in Christmas\u2019 frolic, engaged In\nnoisy demonstrations and afterward pre\ndicted that the turn was at hand, that\nthe market was slated for substantial\ngains, and that \u201cthe clouds had rolled\naway,\"\nThe bulk of the trade centered largely\nin the Hills, Union Pacific, Missouri Pa\niy and Pennsylvania. Smelter did\nwell.\nA good bank statement, higher Lon\ndon and investment buying was respon\nsible for the better feeling.\nThe closing prices for the stocks\nnamed on the dates given were as fol\nlows:\nCopper.\nAm, Car Foundry\nIce...\nSRRsarunsn\u2019\nJisRages\n\u201cWe have to be awful economical\ndown at our house,\u201d said the boy;\n\u201cthere's a big family.\u201d\n\u201cYes?\u201d inquiringly.\n\u201cThat's so, for \u2018fair! My biggest\nbrother is a bartender, and, of course,\nhas to wear a white coat; so ma buys\na whole suit for him, says wearing the\noveralls saves his pants. When they've\nbeen washed a few times, of course,\nthey don\u2019t look nice enough for a bar\ntender, so ma gets him new ones and\nhands the other to Bill. Bill works ir\na meat market.\u201d\n\nPs two years out of them that way,\neh?\"\n\u201cThen dad's a painter? when the white\nsuit Ss too dirty for Bill, dad wears\nit as long as he can to paint in. Course,\nin time they get pretty well caked up\nwith paint, then ma uses them for kind\nHag the fire, and being soaked with\npaint, they burn fine.\u201d\n\u201cSo that's the end of them? Well,\nyou certainly do\u2014-\"\n\u201cNo! Ma uses them again, along with\nthe wood ashes, to make soap of.\u201d\n\u201cYou don't say!\"\n\u201cYep! After that she pours the soan\nsuds on the back garden. Best thing\nin the world, she says, 10 make things\ngrow.\u201d Puck.\n\u201cI must have made some mistake,\u201d\nmuttered Mrs. Zogger, looking in the\noven of her kitchen range, says the\nChicago Tribune. \u201cI was sure I put six\npotatoes in here to bake, but there\nseems to be only five.\u201d\nShe counted them again, but with the\nsame result.\nThen she looked at the cake she had\nput in at the same time.\nars doing all right, anyway,\u201d she\nsaid.\n\u201cBelinda,\u201d said Mr. Zogger, looking at\nthe slice of cake that lay on the plate\nbefore him, \u201cwhat the Sam Hill is the\nmatter with this?\u201d\n\u201cYou needn't eat it if you don't like\nit, Theophilus, retorted Mrs. r,\nwith spirit.\n\u201cOh, I'll eat it, all right, but I'm won\ndering what makes this island of white\nin the middle of a sea of yellow.\u201d\n\u20188he examined the slice of cake, and a\ntriumphant smile illumined her face.\n\u201cI just knew I had put six potatoes in\nthat oven yesterday,\u201d she exclaimed.\nne of them fell down through the top\nshelf.\u201d\nDull, But Little Change.\nTHE ECONOMICAL BOUSF\nPOTATOES.\nNEW YORK, Dec. 28.\u2014Money on call\nwas nominally 156 per cent toda;. The\nmarket was governed by the prepara\ntions for the year-end financing, when\nmuch of the $185,000,000 in January div\nidends and interest payments has to\nbe provided. The currency premium\nFiled weaker. With few bids for large\nlots, touching 1% per cent Monday, 1\nTuesday, Wednesday, holiday, 1 Thurs\nday, Friday.\n\nCall loans were made at 2% and 6\nper cent, averaging about 2. Time\nmoney during the week continued in\nactive, owing to the dearth of funds.\nRates 15 per cent for 30 days, 12 to 15\nper cent for 60 to days, 8 to 10 per\ncent for four months, 8 per cent for six\nmonths.\nMercantile paper was slightly Im\nproved In une, but the improvement\nwas rather in sentiment as to the fu\nture than in actual ir:dce, which was\nlight and confined t, a few buyers.\nRates were quoted nominally, at 3\nto 10 per cent for all kinds,\nSterling experienced a violent decline\nthis week, demand rates falling from\n485 to 4.84%; cables, from 4.88% to\n4.86%. Fluctuations were wide and very\nirregular. Monday's market showed a\ndecline of 1 cent: Tuesday a further\ndecline of to 1 cent: Thursday, a\nrally of 1%; yesterday's decline of\nto 1% and today a decline of XK to 1\n\nA\nThe feigning of death by certain ani\nmals for the purpose of deceiving their\nenemies and thus securing immunity is\none of the greatest of the many evi\ndences of their intelligent ratiocination.\nThis simulation is not confined to any\nparticular family, order or species of an\nimal, but exists in many, from the very\nlowest to the highest. It is found even\nIn the vegetable kingdom, the weil\nknown sensitive plant being ao inter\nesting example. The action of this plant\nis purely reflex, as can be proved by ob\nservation and experiment, and is not,\ntherefore, a process of intelligence.\n\n\n\n\n1\n\n\n\nAn experimenter, writing in Wissen\nfur Alle, says that he has seen the feign.\ning of death in some of the lowest ani\nmals known to science. Sometime ago,\nwhile examining the inhabitants of a\ndrop of pond ter under a high-power\nlens, he noti several rhizcpods busily\nfeeding on the minute buds of an alga.\nThese rhisopods suddenly drew in their\nhalrlike filaria and sank to the bottom,\nto all appearances dead. The cause was\nfound to be the presence of a water\nlouse, an animal which feeds on these\nanimalculae. It likewise sank to the\nbottom, and, after looking at the rhizo\npods, swam away, evidently regarding\nthera as dead and unfit for f A\n\n\n\n\ni\n\nThis was not an accidental occurrence,\nfor the observer has seen the same won\nderful performance twice since. Through\ntLe agency of what sense, he asks, did\nthese little creatures discover the ap\nproach of their enemys? Is it possible\nthat they and other microscopic animals\nhava eyes and ears so exceedingly small\nthat lenses of the very highest power\ncannot make them visibie, or are they\npossessors of s\u00e9nses utterly unknown to\nand incapable of being appreciated by\nmzn? Science can neither affirm nor\ndeny either of these zuppositions.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nMost animals are slain for food by\nother animals. Most of the carnivora\nand insectivore prefer freshly killed food\nto carrion. They will not touch tainted\nmeat when they can procure fresh.\n\u2018Hence, when they come upon their prey\n\u2018apparently dead, they will leave it alone\nand go in search of other gRarry, unless\nthey are very hungry. ainted sub\n\u2018stances are dangerous to get into the\nstomach. Certain ptomaines render it\nSometimes very poisonous. Long years\nof experience have taught this fact to\n\u2018animals, and, therefore, most of them\nlet dead or seemingly dead creatures\nalone\n\n\n\nSome pertinent words were spoken by\nH. G. Wells at a recent dinner of ile\nInstitute of Journalists in London. He\ndenied that any just distinction can be\nmade between literature and journalism,\nexcept that the one claims immortality\nand the other does not. \u201cSome books\nlast longer than others,\u201d he said, \u201cand\nsome topics last for centuries and\ncenturies, but I do not believe that any\nbooks last for all time.\u201d\nTo this extent agreement may be had\nwith Mr. VWells\u2014the value of a book\ncannot be judged merely according to\nthe time it continues to be read. The\nfirst appeal of evety author must be to\nhis own generation, comments a writer\nin the London Dally News, and that\ngeneration has as much right to judge\nwhether he is worthy or unworthy as\nany succeeding generation. If his con\ntemporaries embrace him and posterity\ndenounces him, that he may well say,\nis not because posterity is wiser, but\nbecause it lacks just that quality to\nwhich he appealed in his contemporaries.\nIf he has profoundly affected one gen\neration alone then he has profoundly\naffected the history of the race. \u2014Ex\nchange.\nTHE WASHINGTON TT-,\u00a3S, SUNDAY, DECEMBER 29, 1907.\nNew York Bond Mar. .t\n\nNEW YORK, Dec. 28.\u2014United States\nGovernment bonds:\n2's registered, 1930, 106@105%.\n2'= coupon, 1830, 105% @106.\n3's registered, 1908, 101%4@102%.\n3's coupon, 1808 101'4@102%.\n4's small bonds, 100%.\n4's registered, 1925, 119@121.\n4'd coupon, 1925, 119@121.\nPanama Canal 2's, registered, 103%@101\n4's Philippine 4's, 110%.\nSTOCK BEXCHANGE BUND TRANSAC\nTIONS.\nVirginia cef. 6's, Brown Bros. cer\ntificates, 24.\nImperial Japanese first series, 4%'s\nR67%.\nAmerican Tobacco \u00a7's, 96.\nAmerican Tgbacco 4's, 59%.\nCentral Georgia consol 5's, 96.\nDelaware and Hudson 4's, 94,\nDistilling Sc. C \u00a7's, 66%.\nErie consol 4's, 84%.\nNew York Central, 54's, 891%.\nNew York Central 1i 8S. 3%'s, 74%.\nNorfolk and Western consol 4's, 2%.\nNorthern Pacific 4's, 10044.\nPennsylvania 4's, 1906, 88%.\nPennsylvania 3%'s, 1012, 901%.\nPennsylvania 3%'s, 1915, 87%.\nReading 4's, 93%.\nSouthern Pacific collateral \u00a5's, S114.\n\u201cSouthern Pacific refunding 4's, 88.\nSouthern Ralilway 4's, 89.\nUnion Pacific first 4's, 100%.\nUnion Pacific convertible 4's, $6.\nUnited States Steel S. F. 5's, 85.\nUnited States Steel registered, 8414.\nUnited States Steel registered, 85%.\nTota] sales, $1,575,000.\n\nNEW YORK MONEY\nI i\nFEIGNING OF DEATH\nANIMAL'S STRATEGY\nJOURNALISM AND LITERATURE.\nHEELING PLANTS\n19 RESURE WORK\nWT NEW YEAR\nGreater Part of Fifteen\nThousand Man Will\nGet Jobs.\nCity and Suburban \u00a7's.............. 93%;\nCUTMIDIA. B Been rs3exsnunsnceroowns 10234\n06%\nOutlook Bright After\nWorst Autumn in\nFourteen Years.\n107%\nvee 100%\n106s\n*Capital Traction 121%\nWash. Rwy. and Elec. Pil. cnnnss 66%\nool and oan. Steam boat... 230\nWHEELING, W. Va., Dec. 28 ~The\nindustrial depression, which has affected\nsomething like 15000 men in Wheeling\nand the adjacent Ohlo valley, due en\ntirely to the stringency in the money\nmarket, has apparently been lifted, for\norders were received today to put the\ngreater number of idle men to work\nJanuary 2. In Wheeling at least 4, 000\nmen who have been jdle most of two\nmonths will get started then, and in\nadjacent manufacturing establishments\n7,000 to 8,000 men are ordered to work\neither Monday or Thursday mornings.\nTYPE MACHINE STOCKS.\nShengeutaler a ELE EET Th\na\n\n\nFB i\n\nceeeeeeses\nThe return of prosperity applies to all\nclasses of workers. The American\nsheet and tin plate works, a subsidiary\nof the United States Steel Company,\nhag ordered 2,600 men at their Laughlin\ntin plate plant on Monday morning.\nTheir La Belle plant. with 200 men, will\nresume work in a week, and the Aeina\nstandard sheet mill, employing 2,300 men,\nwill start half its mills Monday, and the\nother half in a week.\n\n.,eooeoeneeeeei\nWashington Ioan and Trust......\nSAVINGS BANK STOCKS.\ndog EA ies saressrrnsanne 2%\n*Union SaVINES ..evuenrononnnonnonn. 220 280\nFIRE INSURANCE STOCKS\nArlington .........cceeevmneenrnenenns 3\nLR ho BE BE ET eTTTETT n\nfA IRREIRERY anne ss sess snuusnes\n\u2018The only important plants in Wheeling\nand vicinity not to resume next week\nare the Bellaire steel plant of ths United\nStates Steel Company and the Klverside\ntube works, owned by one of the sub,\nsidlary companies of the same corpora\ntion. In both places extensive repairs\nare being made.\niriresidts RE DEE RET\nGerman American. SR\n\nBRetiopoisan\ni nn errn sansa\nPog oe  Suatewreants hod\nRiggs PR dh a ts a A a a 8%\ni TITLE INSURANCE\namills. CrSRsas seas atts e test ane 6\nMISCELLANEOUS STOCKS\nOf the 15,000 miners employed within\na radius of ten miles of Wheeling, prin.\ncipally on the Ohio side of the river, all\nwill go back to work Monday. Of these\nabout one-half have been idle because\nof the inability to get money to carry\non their work. The coal companies wil\ncontinue working s eadily until April L\nGrapho. COM....eererereeneernscnsens wes\nrr eretrassEAsRAL SLE ae ne Sou 5\n200\n\nConsidering the fact that Wheeling\nand Its adjacent industrial towns have\nhad the worst fall since the panic ot\n1888. the outlook for the first of the year\nis the most encouraging for a long time.\nDemand for Workmen\nComing to Department\nShows Revival of Trade\n\n\nAccording to reports that are coming\nto the division of Information of the\n\u2018Department of Comm\u00e9rce and Labor,\nindustrial conditions the country over\nare beginning to show a decided im\nprovement. This is Indicated by the\nfact that applications are coming In\nfrom business establishments, commer\ncial bodies, and the like, for workmen.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nUp to October 1, letters came in to the\ndivision of information offering positiuns\nto about 200,000 people. Then, the finan\ncial situation became unsatisfactory and\nthere was a cessation in the re. uests for\nemployes. In the last week \u201chere has\nbeen a renewal of the demand. At the\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\npartment of Commerce and Labor\nthis is looked on as the most encourag\ning possible sign of a revival of business\nand as the ending of the movement for\nthe laying off of employes that for a\ntime attained large proportions.\n\n\nHs\n\nFrom the West demands are coming\nin for farm laborers and the expecta\ntion is that this demand will be strong\nwith the approach of spring.\n\n\n\n\nLOW-CLASS FOOD.\n\u201cThey say that music is the food of\nlove,\"\n\n\n\u2018Then how would you classify raz\ntime?\"\n\n\n\n\u201cAs hash.\u201d\u2014Louizville Courier-Journal.\n\nBanking hours: a. m. to 3 p. m.; Saturdays, 9 a. m. to 12 and 6 to 8 p. m. On the ist, 2d, 34, 15th, 16th,\n17th, and last day of each month, 9 to p. m.,, excep: when falling on a holiday or Saturday.\n\n\n\n{ia Xl\nOFFICERS:\nB. F. Saul,\nPresident.\nTRH AS\nwe\naR Nady!\nmE ae\nBrice J. Moses,\nVice President\nMipsis\nbu\nLif\nliald\nfal J\n1]\ny\nIv\nAlex. 8. Clarke,\nSecretary.\nHoward Moran,\nTreasurer.\nN. E. Branch:\n7th and H Sts. N.E.\nDIRECTORS:\nCarl Auerbach,\nMichael J. Colbert,\nAttorney.\ndali,\nFIRE SAVINGS Em NK fa Eaetek, ELE wl Anthony Gaegler,\ni J re a HY ET ok CH 4 Z oP Hu John B. Geier,\nFl J Herrmanz.\n\u00a3s n Johnsou,\nWm. Miller,\n{a\ni\nHTT\nAlex. S. Clarke\nRAH Tamme,\n[RHR mis agsid\nmn\n3 HEAD OFFICE BF sam\nI. 7th and Mass. Ave. N.W, James P- Sioa,\nInterest paid on Savings Accounts.\nO Computed twice a year.\nCommerciai Accounts Solicit=d.\nSafe Deposit Boxes for rent from $3 a year up.\nDrafts on ali Foreign Countries.\nS. W. Branch:\n436 7th St. S. W.\nUnder Supervision of U. S, Treasury.\nWASHINGTON STOCKS\nINBETTER DEMAND\n\nInterest Centers in Wash\nington Railway Pre\nferred Stock.\nWashington Gas \u20ac8.....c.ccueu... we MN 106\nWash, Gan. Cart. 8'8...corcsronsorsss 102 105\nCapital Traction R. R. im\nAnacostia and Potomac FR\nCapital Traction Interests\nMay Enter Directory of.\nCompetitor.\noT 100\nMuch interest centers in the annual\nmeeting of the shareholders of the\n\u2018Washington Railway and Electric\nCompeny to be held, January 18. At\n\u2018that meeting, so runs the story, in\nterests friendly to the Capital Traction\nCompany, one of the best managed and\nmost successful street railroad prop\n\u2018erties ia the country, will step into\nthe directory of its local competitor.\n\u2018That the financial interests of the city\nare opposed to any such movemeni is\nby no means the case; on the con\ntrary they look upon it as the best\nthing that could happen .for the bene\nfit of the traction interests of Wash\nington.\nBRAT AXRCANOEY spcssssnsspassinson 121%\noo BY. And Bloc. oom 2\nSuahnsn, Gus hassssssnsarsalensnss ae\nChesa. and Pot. ire 54\nOne of the rumors that is nearly as\nold as the year 197 has to do with\nthe possible elevation of Secretary Loeb\nto the presiaency of the Washington\nRallway and Electric Company. It\nhas been repeated time and again with\nvarious changes and frequent el:mina\ntions of ie gentleman from consid\neration in the capacity suggested.\nTime alone will demonstrate whether\nMr, Loeb is to sever his relations with\nPresident Roosevelt in the immed ate\nfuture.\nThe rumor in connection with the en\ntrance of Capital Traction iaterests on\nthe Washington Railway Company's\nboard is more promising of results than\nthe change of presidents,\nWhatever the outcome of the annual\nmeeting, the stock of the company has\nreceived excellent support,\nA few months ago it was selling\naround 72 and better, and then, at a\ntime when there was no buying of\nstocks, it dropped down in the low 0's,\nrallying slowly a few days ago to 63,\nand then to 64, and with a quick jump\nto 65 to 66, and for a final to 67 for a\nsmall lot. Comparatively little business\nwas transacted at the advance, although\nseveral hundred shares sold on Friday.\nRest of Market Slow.\nThe rest of the market was slow, but\nthe promise of better times is much\nbrighter for Washington than it is for\nNew Work. This city has gone through\nthe panic with never a touch\u2014save as\nbrokers maneuvered to keep the lid\nclamped down tight on the Exchange\nir order to prevent the market from\ngetting started on the tobo and,\nas bankers have conserved thelr re\nsources as against possible contingen\ncles.\nBusiness continued as if no gne knew\nanything of the panicky throes going\non all over the country and securities\ndid not sag to any serious extent.\nThe chances for renewed activity are\nexcellent. There have been ind!-ations\n\u2018along this line for more than week.\nOn Thursday of this week one of the\nbrokers announced his readiness to loan\ncash on security collateral.\nThis was welcomed with.a =%out, as\nbearing out the promise of a public ad\n\u2018dress on Tuesday In which beiter things\nwere prophesied.\nCapltal Traction shares are not quite\n\u2018as strong as they have been for some\ntime, the latest sales being \u00abt 122 and\nSome stock is being l'ig\u00ae idated\nthat has been over the cet for a\ntime. A feature of the week las been\nsome little Inquiry for bank stocks\nwhich is also encouraging.\nMergenthaler transactions have been\nmit to a few odd lots, not enough\nto warrant the assumption of the prices\nas a fair evidence of market values.\n\nMitchell Mining has been slow and\nsteady. Greene Cananea neglected.\nBonds have been in fair demand. The\nclosing bid and asked prices aside from\nthe Washington Rallway shares show\nlittle change for more than a Treek.\nNow Better.\nWashington Prices\n1\nWashington Gas 4's, $100@100.\nCapital Traction \u00a7's, $500@110%.\nWi n Rallway and Electric \u00a2's,\n$1.000@74, $1,000@74.\nFiremen\u2019's Fire Insurance, 25@19%.\nAfter call\u2014Potomac Electric &'s, $1,000\nGAS BONDS.\nMetropolitan R. R. \u00a7's....